<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3419&amp;p=25023#p25023"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[safe areas for ntsc tv on the NES]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=3419&amp;p=25023#p25023"><![CDATA[
All analog TVs have some degree of "overscan" (that is, the portion of the screen that's cut off at the edges).  The portions of the screen that get cut off will vary depending on the TV set, so there's no hard rule.  One of my TV's cuts off around 14 pixels from the top and only a couple from the bottom.  Another TV cuts off around 8 pixels from both the top and the bottom (this is more typical).<br /><br />Overscan is not an issue on the left or right side of the screen, because the NES generates margins on both sides to allow for overscan.  However, graphics near the left or right side might still get cut off due to screen curvature.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=360">dvdmth</a> — Thu Jun 14, 2007 6:33 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
